ing to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":42,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Pyncheon was born in 1340, in London, England, her father, William Pynchon, was 22 and her mother, Jane Empson, was 20. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Chickley. She died in 1400, in Higham Ferrers, Northamptonshire, England, at the age of 60, and was buried in Higham Ferrers, Northamptonshire, England."},"et":{"1340–1400":"1340–1400","1335–1400":"1335–1400","1337–Male":"1337–Surnud","1364–1443":"1364–1443","1364–1427":"1364–1427","1366–1439":"1366–1439","1368–Female":"1368–Surnud","1370–Male":"1370–Surnud","1318–1389":"1318–1389","1320–1368":"1320–1368","1340":"1340","Abt 1368":"umbes 1368","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1368":"1368","1335":"1335","1389":"1389","1400":"1400","1366":"1366","1443":"1443","1364":"1364","1320":"1320","1318":"1318","1439":"1439","1427":"1427","Chippenham, Wiltshire, England":"Chippenham, Wiltshire, England","Maidstone, Kent, England, United Kingdom":"Maidstone, Kent, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Higham Ferrers, Northamptonshire, England":"Higham Ferrers, Northamptonshire, England","London, England":"London, England","Higham Ferrers,Northampton,England":"Higham Ferrers, Nor